Blocks.childText: TIME AND ETERNITY-HEAVEN Rivers of life divine I see, 3 Ten thousand to their endless home And trees of paradise This solemn moment fiv ; I see a world of spirits bright, And we are to the margin come, Who taste the pleasures there ; And we expect to die. They all are robed in spotless white, His militant embodied host, And conquering palms they bear. With wishful looks we stand, And long to see that happy coast, 4 o what are all my sufferings here, And reach the heavenly land. If, Lord, thou count me meet With that enraptured host to appear, 4 Our old companions in distress And worship at thy feet ! We haste again to see, Give joy or grief, give ease or pain, And eager long for our release, Take life or friends away, And full felicity. But let me find them all again E'en now by faith we join our hands In that eternal day. With those that went before ; CHARLES WESLEY. And greet the blood-besprinkled bands On the eternal shore. FOURTH PART. 5 Our spirits, too, shall quickly join, 1033 Communion with saints in heaven. Like theirs with glory crowned, 1 COME, let us join our friends above And shout to see our Captain's sign, That have obtained the prize, To hear his trumpet sound. And on the eagle wings of love o that we now might grasp our Guide! To joys celestial rise. O that the word were given Let all the saints terrestrial sing, Come, Lord of hosts, the waves divide, And land us all in heaven! With those to glory gone; CHARLES WESLEY. For all the servants of our King, In earth and heaven, are one. Doxology. 2 One family we dwell in him, THE God of mercy be adored, One church above, beneath, Who calls our souls from death, Though now divided by the stream, Who saves by his redeeming word, The narrow stream, of death. And new-creating breath; One army of the living God, To praise the Father, and the Son, To his command we bow; And Spirit all-divine,- Part of his host have crossed the flood, The One in Three, and Three in One,- And part are crossing now. Let saints and angels join. ISAAC WATTS. BURLINGTON. C. M. JOHN FRECKLETON BURROWES. 385
